\begin_layout Standard
The maximum entropy model is derived by Wilson (1970). We follow that process but work in probabilities rather than trips because we regard the latter as random variables whereas the probabilities are measures. We begin by constructing the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula \(\mathcal{L}\)
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\label{eq:lagrangian}
\mathcal{L} =   \sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}p_{ij}lnp_{ij}+\lambda_{0}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}p_{ij}-1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}\sum_{j=1}^{n}p_{ij}-p_{i*}
+\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}\sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{ij}-p_{*j}+\beta\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}p_{ij}c_{ij}-\overline{c}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula \(\mathcal{L}\)
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula \(p_{ij}\)
\end_inset

 and setting the result to zero delivers the maximum entropy model thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:basicmodel}
p_{ij}=e^{-\lambda_{0}}e^{-\lambda_{i}}e^{-\lambda_{j}}e^{-\beta c_{ij}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing both sides and recognising that 
\begin_inset Formula \(\lambda_{0}\)
\end_inset

is a constant we find that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:defnZ}
e^{-\lambda_{0}}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}e^{-\lambda_{i}}e^{-\lambda_{j}}e^{-\beta c_{ij}}=Z
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the constant Z as it corresponds to the partition function of statistical physics and write the model as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:model}
p_{ij}=\frac{e^{-\lambda_{i}}e^{-\lambda_{j}}e^{-\beta c_{ij}}}{Z}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now take logarithms, multiply by 
\begin_inset Formula \(\frac{-p_{ij}}{\beta}\)
\end_inset

 and sum over 
\begin_inset Formula \(i,j\)
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:thermoState}
\frac{1}{\beta}S=U+PV-G
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where S is entropy, U is mean energy, PV is 
\begin_inset Formula \(\frac{\lambda_{i}+\lambda_{j}}{\beta}\)
\end_inset

 and G is 
\begin_inset Formula \(\ln Z\)
\end_inset

. These terms are used to show the correspondence of the model to the classical gas model (Callen 1985) where G is the Gibbs free energy, and PV the product of pressure, P and volume V.
\end_layout

