\begin_layout Standard
The standard method for calibration, i.e.
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

finding the value of 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta\)
\end_inset

 is to run the model with varying values of 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta\)
\end_inset

 in a search to find that value which gives a mean trip cost sufficiently close to the observed trip cost(Hyman and Wilson 1969; Dios Ortuzar and Willumsen 2011). The method of running the model is to use a Furness iteration (Furness 1965) to balance Origins and Destinations for a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta\)
\end_inset

. This introduces the balancing factors 
\begin_inset Formula \(e^{-\lambda_{i}}e^{-\lambda_{j}}\)
\end_inset

 of equation 2 which relate to the rents of equation 10. The iteration provides a result in which the balancing factors are unique (Lemma 2 Evans 1970) which ensures that the resulting trip matrix, given 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta\)
\end_inset

, is also unique. In the method of calibration by rent, instead of matching observed and modelled mean trip costs, we match observed and modelled rents by minimising the J divergence (Rohde 2016) between them. The J divergence is an information based semimetric measure which satisfies all the conditions for a distance measure apart from the triangle inequality. In particular it is finite,symmetric and decomposable. The J divergence between two probability distributions,
\begin_inset Formula \(p\left(x_{i}\right)\)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \(q\left(y_{i}\right)\)
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:jeffries}
J=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}\left(p\left(x_{i}\right)-q\left(y_{i}\right)\right)\ln\left(\frac{p\left(x_{i}\right)}{q\left(y_{i}\right)}\right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

